  <subsection>
    <title>The Magnitude of a Vector</title>
    <p>
      By definition, vectors have both direction and magnitude (or
      length). We now investigate how to calculate the magnitude
      of a vector. Since a vector <m>\vv</m> can be represented
      by a directed line segment, we can use the distance formula to
      calculate the length of the segment. This length is the
      <em>magnitude</em> of the vector <m>\vv</m> and is denoted <m>|\vv|</m>.
    </p>

    <activity xml:id="A-9-2-7">
    
    <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" margins="0%">
      <figure xml:id="F-9-2-vector-magnitude_a" >
        <caption>The vector defined by <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.</caption>
          <image width="73%" source="images/fig-9-20" />
      </figure>
      <figure xml:id="F-9-2-vector-magnitude_b" >
        <caption>An arbitrary vector, <m>\vv</m>.</caption>
          <image width="73%" source="images/fig-9-21" />
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>A = (2,3)</m> and <m>B = (4,7)</m>, as shown in <xref ref="F-9-2-vector-magnitude_a">Figure</xref>. Compute <m>|\overrightarrow{AB}|</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2 \rangle</m> be the vector in <m>\R^2</m> with components <m>v_1</m> and <m>v_2</m> as shown in <xref ref="F-9-2-vector-magnitude_b">Figure</xref>. Use the distance formula to find a general formula for <m>|\vv|</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2, v_3 \rangle</m> be a vector in <m>\R^3</m>. Use the distance formula to find a general formula for <m>|\vv|</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>\vu = \langle 2,3\rangle</m> and <m>\vv =
                      \langle -1,2\rangle</m>.  Find <m>|\vu|</m>, <m>|\vv|</m>, and
                      <m>|\vu+\vv|</m>.  Is it true that <m>|\vu + \vv| = |\vu|+|\vv|</m>?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Under what conditions will <m>|\vu+\vv| = |\vu|+|\vv|</m>? (Hint: Think about how <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vu+\vv</m> form the sides of a triangle.)
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            With the vector <m>\vu = \langle 2,3\rangle</m>, find the
                      lengths of <m>2\vu</m>, <m>3\vu</m>, and <m>-2\vu</m>, respectively, and use proper notation to label your results.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>t</m> is any scalar, how is <m>|t\vu|</m>
                      related to <m>|\vu|</m>?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            A <em>unit vector</em> is a vector whose magnitude is 1.
                      Of the vectors <m>\textbf{i}</m>, <m>\textbf{j}</m>, and <m>\textbf{i} + \textbf{            j}</m>, which are unit vectors?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Find a unit vector <m>\vv</m> whose direction is the same as
                      <m>\vu = \langle 2, 3\rangle</m>. (Hint: Consider the result of part (g).)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                In this case we have <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = \langle 2,4\rangle</m>, so
                <me>
                  |\overrightarrow{AB}|  = \sqrt{2^2+4^2} = \sqrt{20}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The distance formula tells us that
                <me>
                  |\vv| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The distance formula tells us that
                <me>
                  |\vv| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2+v_3^2}.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                We have <m>|\vu| = \sqrt{13}</m>, <m>|\vv| = \sqrt{5}</m>, while <m>|\vu+\vv| = |\langle 1,5\rangle| = \sqrt{26}</m>. So <m>|\vu + \vv| \neq |\vu|+|\vv|</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, and <m>\vu+\vv</m> form the sides of a triangle, and <m>\vu+\vv</m> provides a straight path from the tail of <m>\vu</m> to the tip of <m>\vv</m>, the length of <m>\vu+\vv</m> should be longer that the sum of the lengths of the other sides, unless <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> are on the same ray.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                In this case we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>|2\vu| \amp = |\langle 4,6 \rangle | = \sqrt{52}</mrow>
                  <mrow>|3\vu| \amp = |\langle 6,9 \rangle | = \sqrt{117}</mrow>
                  <mrow>|-2\vu| \amp = |\langle -4,-6 \rangle | = \sqrt{52}</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Note that if <m>\vu = \langle u_1, u_2\rangle</m>, then
                <me>
                  |t\vu| = |\langle tu_1, tu_2 \rangle | = \sqrt{t^2u_1^2 + t^2u_2^2} = \sqrt{t^2}\sqrt{u_1^2+u_2^2} = |t||\vu|.
                </me>
                This same argument applies in any dimension, so we conclude that
                <me>
                  |t\vu| = |t||\vu|.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>|\textbf{i}| = |\langle 1,0 \rangle | = 1</m>, <m>|\textbf{j}| = |\langle 0,1 \rangle | = 1</m>, and <m>|\textbf{i }+ \textbf{j}| = |\langle 1,1 \rangle | = \sqrt{2}1</m>, we see that only <m>\textbf{i}</m> and <m>\textbf{j}</m> are unit vectors.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                As we saw earlier,
                <me>
                  |t\vu| = |t||\vu|,
                </me>
                So
                <me>
                  \left| \frac{1}{|\vu|} \vu \right| = \frac{1}{|\vu|} |\vu| = 1.
                </me>
                Therefore, the vector <m>\frac{1}{13} \langle 2,3\rangle</m> is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\vu = \langle 2, 3\rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          A vector is any object that possesses the attributes of
            magnitude and direction. Examples of vector quantities are position,
            velocity, acceleration, and force.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Two vectors are equal if they have the
            same direction and magnitude. Notice that position is not considered, so a vector is independent of its location.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>\vu = \langle u_1, u_2, \ldots, u_n \rangle</m> and <m>\vv =
            \langle v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_n \rangle</m> are two vectors in <m>\R^n</m>,
            then their vector sum is the vector
          <me>
            \vu + \vv = \langle u_1+v_1, u_2+v_2, \ldots, u_n+v_n \rangle.
          </me>
          If <m>\vu = \langle u_1, u_2, \ldots, u_n \rangle</m> is a vector in <m>\R^n</m>
          and <m>c</m> is a scalar, then the scalar multiple <m>c\vu</m> is the vector
          <me>
            c\vu = \langle cu_1, cu_2, \ldots, cu_n \rangle.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The magnitude of the vector <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_n
            \rangle</m> in <m>\R^n</m> is the scalar
          <me>
            |\vv| = \sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2+ \cdots + v_n^2}.
          </me>
          A vector <m>\vu</m> is a
            unit vector provided that <m>|\vu| = 1</m>. If <m>\vv</m> is a nonzero vector,
            then the vector <m>\frac{\vv}{|\vv|}</m> is a unit vector with the same
            direction as <m>\vv</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
