      <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-2-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle 1, -2 \rangle</m>, <m>\vu = \langle 0, 4 \rangle</m>, and <m>\vw = \langle -5, 7 \rangle</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the components of the vector <m>\vu - \vv</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the components of the vector <m>2\vv - 3\vu</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the components of the vector <m>\vv + 2\vu - 7 \vw</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine scalars <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>a \vv + b\vu = \vw.</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In this example we have <m>\vu - \vv = \langle 0-1, 4-(-2) \rangle = \langle -1, 6 \rangle</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  In this example we have <m>2\vv - 3\vu = \langle 2(1)-3(0), 2(-2)-3(4) \rangle = \langle 2, -16 \rangle</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  In this example we have <m>\vv + 2\vu - 7 \vw = \langle 1+2(0)-7(-5), -2+2(4)-7(7) \rangle = \langle 36, -43 \rangle</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Since <m>a \vv + b\vu = \langle a, -2a+4b \rangle</m>, in order for <m>a \vv + b\vu</m> to equal <m>\vw</m> we must have <m>a=-5</m> and <m>-2(-5)+4b = 7</m>. So <m>a=-5</m> and <m>b = -\frac{3}{4}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-2-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vu = \langle 2, 1 \rangle</m> and <m>\vv = \langle 1, 2 \rangle</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the components and draw geometric representations of the vectors <m>2\vu</m>, <m>\frac{1}{2}\vu</m>, <m>(-1)\vu</m>, and <m>(-3)\vu</m> on the same set of axes.
