      <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-2-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Recall that given any vector <m>\vv</m>, we can calculate its length, <m>|\vv|</m>. Also, we say that two vectors that are scalar multiples of one another are <em>parallel</em>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\vv = \langle 3,4 \rangle</m> in <m>\R^2</m>.  Compute <m>|\vv|</m>, and determine the components of the vector <m>\vu = \frac{1}{|\vv|} \vv</m>.  What is the magnitude of the vector <m>\vu</m>?  How does its direction compare to <m>\vv</m>?
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\vw = 3\vi - 3\vj</m> in <m>\R^2</m>.  Determine a unit vector <m>\vu</m> in the same direction as <m>\vw</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\vv = \langle 2, 3, 5 \rangle</m> in <m>\R^3</m>.  Compute <m>|\vv|</m>, and determine the components of the vector <m>\vu = \frac{1}{|\vv|} \vv</m>.  What is the magnitude of the vector <m>\vu</m>?  How does its direction compare to <m>\vv</m>?
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>\vv</m> be an arbitrary nonzero vector in <m>\R^3</m>. Write a general formula for a unit vector that is parallel to <m>\vv</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  We know that <m>|\vv| = \sqrt{3^2+4^2} = 5</m>. So <m>\vu = \frac{1}{|\vv|} \vv = \left\langle \frac{3}{5}, \frac{4}{5} \right\rangle</m>. The magnitude of <m>\vu</m> is <m>|\vu| = \sqrt{\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^2} = 1</m>. Since <m>\vu</m> is a positive scalar multiple of <m>\vv</m>, the vector <m>\vu</m> is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  As in part (a), to find a unit vector in the direction of <m>\vw</m>, we divide <m>\vw</m> by its magnitude. So a unit vector <m>\vu</m> in the same direction as <m>\vw</m> is <m>\vu = \frac{1}{|\vw|} \vw = \frac{1}{\sqrt{18}} \vw = \left\langle \frac{3}{\sqrt{18}}, -\frac{3}{\sqrt{18}} \right\rangle</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We know that <m>|\vv| = \sqrt{2^2+3^2+5^2} = \sqrt{38}</m>. So <m>\vu = \frac{1}{|\vv|} \vv = \left\langle \frac{2}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{3}{\sqrt{38}}, \frac{5}{\sqrt{38}} \right\rangle</m>. The magnitude of <m>\vu</m> is <m>|\vu| = \sqrt{\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{38}}\right)^2  + \left(\frac{3}{\sqrt{38}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{5}{\sqrt{38}}\right)^2} = 1</m>. Since <m>\vu</m> is a positive scalar multiple of <m>\vv</m>, the vector <m>\vu</m> is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>\vv</m> is an arbitrary nonzero vector in <m>\R^3</m>, then the vector <m>\frac{1}{|\vv|} \vv</m> is a unit vector that is parallel to <m>\vv</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
